SIMPLE: linen
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Linen
<hw>Lin"en</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧n"⟦ecr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE., fr.
<ets>lin</ets> linen. See <er>Linen</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Made of linen; <as>as, <ex>linen</ex> cloth; a
<ex>linen</ex> stocking.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Resembling linen cloth; white; pale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Linen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Linen
<hw>Lin"en</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prop. an adj. from OE.
<ets>lin</ets> flax, AS. <ets>l⟦imac⟧n</ets> flax, whence
<ets>l⟦imac⟧nen</ets> made of flax; akin to OS., Icel., & MHG.
<ets>l⟦imac⟧n</ets> flax and linen, G. <ets>lein</ets>,
<ets>leinen</ets>, linen, Sw. <ets>lin</ets> flax, Goth. <ets>lein</ets>
linen, L. <ets>linum</ets> flax, linen, Gr. <grk>li`non</grk>. Cf.
<er>Line</er>, <er>Linseed</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Thread or cloth
made of flax or (rarely) of hemp; -- used in a general sense to include
cambric, shirting, sheeting, towels, tablecloths, etc.; <as>as, bed
<ex>linens</ex></as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧In <xex>linen</xex> white as
milk.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Robert of Brunne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Underclothing, esp. the shirt, as being, in former
times, chiefly made of linen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 3. pl. bed linens -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Linen draper</b></col>, <cd>a dealer in linen.</cd> --
<col><b>Linen prover</b></col>, <cd>a small microscope for counting the
threads in a given space in linen fabrics.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Linen
scroll</b></col>, <col><b>Linen pattern</b></col></mcol>
<fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>an ornament for filling panels, copied from the
folds of a piece of stuff symmetrically disposed.</cd></cs> <-- bed
linens, sheets and pillowcases for a bed. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Linener</ent>⟦br⟧
